[{"id":30471,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>The hydrogen bromide addition in peroxides follows Anti Markovnikov rule.  Anti Markovnikov  addition reaction is found to follow a free radical mechanism. The peroxide compound involved helps in the generation of free radicals. The Anti-Markovnikov rule defines regiochemistry in which the substituent is attached to a less substituted carbon instead of the more substituted carbon.</p><p>The reaction of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mo>-</mo></math>Methylhex-2-ene  with <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>HBr</mi></math> in presence of peroxide, takes place as follows,</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/af7b767c-8d53-40bf-9f4c-761a0924ba2f.png\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 200px;\"/></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math> chiral carbons, here, so, total number of stereoisomers will be <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></msup><mo>=</mo><msup><mn>2</mn><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (27 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30499,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c55c7b42-a9ef-42ca-97a5-480a74967b80-image.png\" style=\"width: 281px; height: 100px;\" /></p><p>Let initial moles of reactant taken <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></math><br />Total moles obtained for benzene sulphonic acid (with <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>%</mo></math> yield <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>60</mn><mo>%</mo></math>)&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></math></p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/695204b0-b9cc-4830-a854-2549f143475e-image.png\" style=\"width: 262px; height: 120px;\" /></p><p>Moles of benzene sulphonic acid before reaction <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>II</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></math></p><p>Moles obtained for phenol (with <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>%</mo></math> yield = <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>50</mn><mo>%</mo></math>)&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></math></p><p>So over all <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>%</mo></math>&nbsp;yield of complete reaction&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>3</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>100</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>30</mn></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (27 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30433,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/kCOwKMoSABzqDwx5P_XsrE2ryukc0x9YMz97p4tvtE4.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/YhM2_5tQp8l5mLSMbTAIRXaWWK_w1QFGYHkrjxolLKw.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/rqW6nhwiaKj2TPbrsMpYKHWmk2dgAdGwK0gF_sYhCFE.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/l-bfq7tizla_wiQnFB0r7jS6DBz5aIX4HgefQWKyh58.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>"],"answer":2,"solution":"Stability order of carbocation\n\n\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/Fkj0IGogs8bt-LknpwVxOr7PLQc54kwPw5At2h3fOqg.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (29 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30624,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["a vinyl group","an isopropyl group","an acetylenic triple bond","two ethylenic double bonds"],"answer":0,"solution":"Vinyl group\n$$\n\\left(\\mathrm{CH}_2=\\mathrm{CH}-\\right)\n$$\non ozonolysis give formaldehyde","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2011","image":null},{"id":30467,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/62d8952f-88aa-42eb-899c-8ec90af39166.png\" style=\"width: 150px; height: 160px;\"/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/78f680c8-394b-456c-8193-bfad13e9ddb1.png\" style=\"width: 145px; height: 162px;\"/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/daf30ab6-bfaa-4bbd-bf0c-9f4b42249caa.png\" style=\"width: 150px; height: 166px;\"/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/b3671630-d712-43d4-959a-55cd64475a10.png\" style=\"width: 160px; height: 172px;\"/>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>In this reaction, the given ether is converted to phenolic derivative and ethyl bromide.</p><p>Treatment of alkenes with hydrobromic acid will result in the formation of alkyl bromides according to Markonvikov's rule. Markonvikov's rule is that when an unsymmetrical reagent adds to an unsymmetrical alkene, the more positive part of the agent goes to the carbon that has more hydrogen atoms.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/2f9f9d27-3994-4347-abe1-14c0fa5edb34.png\" style=\"width: 584px; height: 412px;\"/></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (29 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30512,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["Both Statement I and Statement II are correct.","Both Statement I and Statement II are incorrect.","Statement I is correct but Statement II is incorrect.","Statement I is incorrect but Statement II is correct."],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>As sigma bond is formed along the internuclear axis it is stronger than pi-bond, and due to the presence of pi-bonds alkenes will be more reactive towards electrophilic reagents.Hence they are less stable than alkanes.</p><p>The strength of carbon-carbon double bond is greater than single bond as bond strength is directly proportional to bond order.</p><p>Hence, both the statements are correct.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (24 Jun Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30518,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/15d77764-665d-4d04-9f7d-c7380494f8c4-image.png\" style=\"width: 588px; height: 137px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/b8d3ca83-ef6d-46a5-9d10-94c8c87d0888-image.png\" style=\"width: 699px; height: 109px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/93058673-cb40-4e3d-9bf4-17034caa20b6-image.png\" style=\"width: 603px; height: 137px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/efcf139e-b2e3-4fd5-a2bc-e6104aa6f0fd-image.png\" style=\"width: 711px; height: 104px;\" />"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>In first step nitration occurs by mixture of concentrated nitric acid and concentrated sulphuric acid. From this step nitrobenzene (A) is produced.</p><p>In next step chlorination of nitrobenzene occurs, nitro group is meta directing which orients the incoming electrophile at meta position which results in formation of compound (B).</p><p>In last step, reduction occurs and nitro group is converted into amino group and produces compound (C).</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ff05fc6c-a183-42e6-9083-816b118a6ea4-04374754-4d47-4f50-b1f0-e539aa4d2cd6-image.png\" style=\"width: 943px; height: 124px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (31 Aug Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30462,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5a76b04f-0add-4d0b-97aa-40717a5167a8.png\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 120px;\"/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/fe128690-bd32-4742-8eda-4d3b36d65cbb.png\" style=\"width: 549px; height: 136px;\"/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/4d952e1b-dfda-402f-a20b-5efff88ec83f.png\" style=\"width: 482px; height: 106px;\"/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/99e4f8af-4ebb-4f7e-ac4c-443bb27376cc.png\" style=\"width: 450px; height: 134px;\"/>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<blockquote><p>The reaction is known as hydroboration-oxidation. In this reaction, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>6</mn></msub></math> adds to the double bond of propene, resulting in the formation of an organoborane intermediate. Subsequent treatment with <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math> converts the organoborane intermediate to an alcohol. Hydration follows anti-Markownikoff's rule.</p><p>In this hydration reaction, 1-methylcyclohexene (an alkene) is reacted with aqueous <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math> (formed from water and a strong acid such as <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math>), resulting in Markovnikov addition of water across the pi bond. The product is an alcohol.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/6bd88670-0c2c-4dcc-b3ef-338d5549b889.png\" style=\"width: 547px; height: 375px;\"/></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (30 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30529,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math>-Methylpropene","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math>-Methylcyclopropane","But-<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math>-ene","Cyclobutane"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/eda51cbb-47fa-4b8a-a1a0-6a3fed47c059-image.png\" style=\"width: 368px; height: 125px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (25 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30618,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["1-butene $+\\mathrm{HF}$","2-butanol $+\\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{SO}_4$","Butanoyl chloride $+\\mathrm{AlCl}_3$ then $\\mathrm{Zn}, \\mathrm{HCl}$","Butyl choloride $+\\mathrm{AlCl}_3$"],"answer":2,"solution":"The Friedal-crafts alkylation reaction will give propyl phenyl ketone which further on Clemmenson's reduction will give butyl benzene\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/AIhRhW2aXTtukyNNys4exXJ2JRTBP-d_uxi55rYy6Wg.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (22 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":30597,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["Y will have higher dipole moment and higher boiling point than $\\mathrm{X}$ Y","$\\mathrm{Y}$ will have higher dipole moment and lower boiling point than $\\mathrm{X}$","X will have lower dipole moment and lower boiling point than $\\mathrm{Y}$","$\\mathrm{X}$ will have higher dipole moment and higher boiling point than Y"],"answer":3,"solution":"When 2-butyne is treated with $\\mathrm{H}_2$ /Lindlar's catalyst, compound $\\mathrm{X}$ (cis-2-butene) is produced as the major product; and when treated with $\\mathrm{Na} /$ liq $\\mathrm{NH}_3$ it produces $\\mathrm{Y}$ (trans -2- butene) as the major product. Cisisomer $(\\mathrm{X})$ will have higher dipole moment and higher boiling point than $\\operatorname{trans}(\\mathrm{Y})$.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (15 Apr Shift 2 Online)","image":null},{"id":30420,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{Br}_2 / \\mathrm{Fe} ; \\mathrm{Cl}_2, \\Delta$; alc. KOH","$\\mathrm{Cl}_2 / \\mathrm{Fe} ; \\mathrm{Br}_2 /$ anhy. $\\mathrm{AlCl}_3 ;$ aq. KOH","$\\mathrm{Br}_2 /$ anhy. $\\mathrm{AlCl}_3 ; \\mathrm{Cl}_2, \\Delta$; aq. KOH","$\\mathrm{Cl}_2 /$ anhy. $\\mathrm{AlCl}_3 ; \\mathrm{Br}_2 / \\mathrm{Fe} ;$ alc. KOH"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/hG-mbj7zf9OFgnfFB7fKTsPcn5Ye-DpyqaiCgtaxEcU.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (8 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30588,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<p><img height=\"210\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d9fec025-7ca1-4dd0-8785-5f2e78ca31ef-image.png\" width=\"433\" /></p>","<p><img height=\"91\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ac55394f-1847-401f-8701-4ff3ffa1ec27-image.png\" width=\"246\" /></p>","<p><img height=\"93\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/6e01b693-93f1-4c6a-8503-e034dff86216-image.png\" width=\"200\" /></p>","<p><img height=\"209\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/04e62a81-c2b5-41c6-8c63-6537efef55d1-image.png\" width=\"345\" /></p>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>In Fischer projection formula<br /><br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d67e8b38-729d-4e53-b18e-3b77ba49fec2-image.png\" style=\"width: 599px; height: 213px;\" /><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8594;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#946;</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></math> present&nbsp; and leaving group&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>Cl</mi><mo>-</mo></msup></math> is moderate leaving group so more stable alkene, i.e., Saytzeff&nbsp;product will form.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (12 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30573,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/1df33e53-d0bd-4518-877f-02d6eee79a17.png\" /><br />Number of atoms in one plane = <math><mn>13</mn></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (08 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30576,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f2a840d7-3860-445a-822f-5cd27760109f-image.png\" style=\"width: 250px; height: 72px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/561614a7-9987-4ed6-98b8-bef61a6ec1ec-image.png\" style=\"width: 250px; height: 54px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f467d990-b11d-4482-9f90-617f0541921e-image.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 64px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/2effe9e5-155c-40d7-a5e5-e5527a0ed6ec-image.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 54px;\" />"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>First step of the reaction is dehydrohalogenation and then ozonolysis.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/491fd501-7427-495f-af2b-bd02dccdd36a-image.png\" style=\"width: 450px; height: 288px;\" /></p><p>The dehydrohalogenation of alkyl halides, another &szlig; elimination reaction, involves the loss of a hydrogen and a halide from an alkyl halide (RX). Dehydrohalogenation is normally accomplished by reacting the alkyl halide with a strong base, such as sodium ethoxide.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (12 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30442,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["4-Ethyl-3,4-dimethyloctane","2,2,3,3-Tetramethylpentane","2,2,4,5-Tetramethylheptane","2,2,4,4-Tetramethylhexane"],"answer":1,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/PPA3I7bTwkUpvoM49AP9U1QgIhp30r-PiA9o-mE5NgA.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (22 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30481,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/58d4eb65-d934-4c16-9869-1506c2c549f2-9896855_A.png\" style=\"width: 150px; height: 332px;\" />&nbsp;","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e5200b6c-d26a-45b9-9692-086d16ec8e89-9896855_B.png\" style=\"width: 150px; height: 255px;\" />&nbsp;","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/cb0b5d78-0195-4a24-bcef-89c26416b6fd-9896855_C.png\" style=\"width: 150px; height: 255px;\" />&nbsp;","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e0adfc28-69d8-466b-a136-bdf5c7b2643d-9896855_D.png\" style=\"width: 150px; height: 255px;\" />&nbsp;"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>When benzene reacts with&nbsp;methylidenecyclohexane, the product X is formed.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/bc592609-ca49-40e6-a86b-f478953f715f-9896855_S.png\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 255px;\" />&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (01 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30556,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0f388b8a-3bf9-458d-9403-a3c19f1d4082-image.png\" style=\"width: 226px; height: 110px;\" />&nbsp;&nbsp;","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e2462b09-a8b1-42d3-a06e-1505e8f212b2-image.png\" style=\"width: 257px; height: 110px;\" />&nbsp;&nbsp;","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7349c8a9-b80b-44d1-b8e1-db4fda3e4f73-image.png\" style=\"width: 242px; height: 110px;\" />&nbsp;&nbsp;","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/8f003c63-f14e-4de7-b726-df1b70c89dea-image.png\" style=\"width: 215px; height: 110px;\" />&nbsp;&nbsp;"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>Due to bulky base at high temperature first reaction is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>E</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math> and produce Hoffman alkene which further show oxidative ozonolysis</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/28dfbad8-e883-49a0-b953-b2a9b6b74667-image.png\" style=\"width: 700px; height: 99px;\" />&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (06 Sep Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30488,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Let <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></math> is the molar mass of the compound <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mo>/</mo><mi>mol</mi></mrow></mfenced></math><br />mass of compound <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mi>mole</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#215;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>molecular</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mass</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>01</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></math></p><p>mass of carbon <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>01</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mn>60</mn><mn>100</mn></mfrac></math>&nbsp;....(i)</p><p>moles of carbon <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>mass</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>of</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>compound</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>molecular</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mass</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>of</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>carbon</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>01</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></mrow><mn>12</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mn>60</mn><mn>100</mn></mfrac></math>&nbsp; ....(ii)</p><p>Thus, moles of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;from combustion <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>4</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow><mn>44</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo></math>0.1 moles of carbon dioxide</p><p>Using POAC,<br />Thus, from (i) and (ii),<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>01</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></mrow><mn>12</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mn>60</mn><mn>100</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>4</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow><mn>44</mn></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>4</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow><mn>44</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mn>100</mn><mn>60</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mn>12</mn><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>01</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>200</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mo>/</mo><mi>mol</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (29 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30436,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/_r1veNYHwix2gTBGlFAX29NHznq8jpQ49qoCCwb8wg4.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/Z02nY94T-Y3MKlTtDURobvV2XQGkTywFW0TO4DzqcZ8.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/PeC3xaxnkmNrWu5RcG-GsL5RHXVt0putin2Xzi91gRg.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/k_FvmQX-GHCI-Joo17zAljY6NdX9M4aHDWT1d-CVruY.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/N2duQphllagxYB-_4gr9j71gnOqleoKbnVGWPRlR8YQ.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (28 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30572,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/660e9110-f359-488b-8d1b-b62382d6c104-image.png\" style=\"width: 114px; height: 146px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f7f1aaa1-1419-4f7d-9639-df1eddae6d55-image.png\" style=\"width: 139px; height: 183px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/2502e53b-3139-4d82-97d7-11f3ec023292-image.png\" style=\"width: 151px; height: 140px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/96ce8860-8a2d-4c0e-a813-a41a37d5cc8a-image.png\" style=\"width: 153px; height: 164px;\" />"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>Since X absorb two molecules of hydrogen on cataytic hydrogenation, it shoulf have to two double bonds.</p><p>Initial reaction is ozonolysis.</p><p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/19QJ.PNG\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 250px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (08 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30472,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c0f53cea-c788-4964-97d5-5b978306d962.png\" style=\"width: 278px; height: 91px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c8c1e3e5-525d-4d18-ac6f-9b8b4b3c78d9.png\" style=\"width: 191px; height: 153px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/3852a4b6-7534-4fa9-9328-97ad5377bc49.png\" style=\"width: 255px; height: 88px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/8ed707b0-b3cd-4c5f-9ac5-a8f176284918.png\" style=\"width: 301px; height: 43px;\" /></p>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>Hydroboration-oxidation of terminal alkenes give primary alcohols. Propene gives propanol. Propanol on oxidation with PCC gives propanal. Propanal undergo nucleophilic addition reaction with methyl magnesium bromide give 2-butanol.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5338f041-4948-41d1-a392-779a0c6acf91.png\" style=\"width: 454px; height: 276px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (15 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30459,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f5ecf5cc-cbbf-425e-8d67-5424b6995e78.png\" style=\"width: 601px; height: 214px;\"/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/577f2b31-d2e5-4a4a-b699-8ec783bb69a3.png\" style=\"width: 455px; height: 212px;\"/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/caa0fdbf-9d1f-438a-867a-7c56fe5570db.png\" style=\"width: 494px; height: 211px;\"/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/6652d6ac-4b7d-4144-9cfd-4da856e7d117.png\" style=\"width: 494px; height: 178px;\"/>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Bromobenzene is treated with <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>conc</mi><mo>.</mo><mo> </mo><msub><mi>HNO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> to give <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>, 4, 6 </mo><mi>trinitrophenol</mi></math> by electrophilic substitution reaction mechanism, which on reaction with <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>NaOH</mi></math> give trinitrophenol. It is also known as picric acid.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d843583a-718a-49ad-9b49-23041d60758f.png\" style=\"width: 734px; height: 451px;\"/></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (31 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30605,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/eddgzzpdqsufixjaxzqnrwknvltraqdjynqdrfomggddntwujv.jpeg\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/rqhtmwswiuvdmcrgxqvbbismstbzrmdsouvajjyowdooubqyft.jpeg\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/spsxblkufabmofekozeddchaqhvjlymouivsbsoofydlbxmykv.jpeg\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/lmzkaiuztgzsjuqanasamqtznnzylekoaqdkzhfcyyjxnrmidt.jpeg\" />"],"answer":0,"solution":"Formation of carbocation is not possible in case of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>CHCl</mi></math>,​because partial double bond character is present in carbon and chlorine bond due to resonance between lone pair of chlorine atom and double bond.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2017 (08 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":30633,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["n-butane","isobutane","1- butene","1- butyne"],"answer":1,"solution":"No Solution Available","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2004","image":null},{"id":30557,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/28ed8306-c58b-4f58-8c94-60d705123b33-image.png\" style=\"width: 146px; height: 210px;\" />&nbsp;&nbsp;","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/47d4dbad-aa99-44f5-9ac5-5f4e776bb691-image.png\" style=\"width: 146px; height: 200px;\" />&nbsp;&nbsp;","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/addd3787-737a-4f90-b37c-3d811fded215-image.png\" style=\"width: 176px; height: 200px;\" />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/16a99e4b-8d32-44e8-a89e-062db3331d2b-image.png\" style=\"width: 153px; height: 200px;\" />&nbsp;&nbsp;"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/81002fbd-d7c8-46f2-8df6-971c9e8fc79b-image.png\" style=\"width: 406px; height: 400px;\" />&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (06 Sep Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30535,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/028148a1-576a-4d65-ac10-989626da6b78-image.png\" style=\"width: 366px; height: 347px;\" /></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>%</mo></math> yield order&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (18 Mar Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30578,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["2 molecules of <img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/6bb88698-05d6-44a1-8a20-142623072b83-image.png\" style=\"width: 86px; height: 31px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/34a588ff-8620-460e-ae8a-4956d2c46500-image.png\" style=\"width: 185px; height: 60px;\" />","2 Molecules of <img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/73c5a392-bc4f-4f5a-86d4-d5d2e9917405-image.png\" style=\"width: 73px; height: 28px;\" />","One molecular of <img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/df87a859-9ae3-4520-ab64-19df2f611308-image.png\" style=\"width: 73px; height: 28px;\" /> and one molecular of <img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/710ee5b2-8603-42c2-a97a-ff442bc7d4b5-image.png\" style=\"width: 84px; height: 29px;\" />"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>The reaction will be;</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/751c5266-cafa-403c-8443-bc581b41ec33-image.png\" style=\"width: 474px; height: 265px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (12 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30598,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/DeJskMhDX5M8JS4brKF44wf8U3TyPG1gOZKAJ1dqFaU.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/PZ9hvlJzoeI1PXyYdVehhtnZPVr2wgw2KO851jQLkkw.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/dY7g4Eto_UrAfelUSmDdjfFkyu0XZWv6Kl9-kCekbG4.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ABMxMxBM9s74TwjYqf66hFLkQ5r_27NxRI43tyNGoWU.original.fullsize.png\"><br>"],"answer":0,"solution":"Note: In the given reaction a molecule of $\\mathrm{HCl}$ is lost and $\\mathrm{C}=\\mathrm{C}$ double bond is formed. Thus it is dehydrohalogenation reaction.\nNitro group is electron withdrawing group. Hence increases the acidity of $\\mathrm{H}$ atom (attached to $\\mathrm{C}$ atom bearing nitro group) which is removed easily. Further the newly formed double bond is in conjugation with nitro group.\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0Y-pUsuIdxQlmtM75eNgOgkqe1WY1Rkw5n_LlQt8Bpk.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (15 Apr Shift 2 Online)","image":null},{"id":30525,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["The reaction is not possible in acidic medium","Both compounds A&nbsp;and B&nbsp;are formed equally","Compound A will be the major product","Compound B&nbsp;will be the major product"],"answer":2,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/3ad212d3-2ec9-4a1c-a52f-c5ae3557a8b8-image.png\" style=\"width: 334px; height: 306px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (27 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30579,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/2a7c0713-f91d-4011-8a11-77c400e55be0-image.png\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 115px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/569090a3-47cf-428c-9d31-a0a8d7f9648b-image.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 165px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/dd313fd1-8d0c-4080-8c82-e955d80d7875-image.png\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 99px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/be5bfdb2-4c2a-4cf8-bcfb-d03cfd9945e3-image.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 138px;\" />"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>We know that&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>AlCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;is a lewis acid. It can give Friedel Crafts reactions.&nbsp;Here, we can see that&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>AlCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;acts as a lewis acid and accepts the electron pair from the chlorine atom. This forms<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8722;</mo><msub><mi>AlCl</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>.</mo></math>&nbsp;Alongside this, a carbocation is also formed.</p><p>Now, this carbocation is an electrophilic carbon. So, benzene rings can give electrophilic substitution reactions here. So, as a result, the double bond of benzene will attack on the carbocation and a C-C bond will be formed there. Then after losing a proton, the carbon ring becomes aromatic. This, we obtain a compound which has two ring structures. One ring is aromatic and the other is not aromatic.</p><p>Friedel-Craft alkylation takes place to give a six membered ring.<br /><br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/63bfa5e0-9906-40fc-a13e-5d39a16cd2c8-7391c478-7a54-4f22-b819-6cc5cc2074b9-image.png\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 234px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (10 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30444,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"Compounds which can not undergo Friedel Crafts reaction are\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/1GQr2wTB1M_n_Mbbsl0PQLXSQ1_8eVu0Ij_XC3YK_as.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (09 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30583,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["Reimer Tiemann reaction","Friedel Craft's alkylation","Acetylation of aniline","Friedel Craft's acylation"],"answer":1,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/2df21049-5a95-4d8f-8e3a-6cb5c469c331-image29.png\" /><br />In Friedel crafts alkylation product obtained is more activated due to the activating nature of the alkyl group and hence poly substitution will take place.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (08 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30400,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["$90$","$118$","$160$","$125$"],"answer":1,"solution":"Addition of $Br_2$ to styrene (X) yields 1,2-dibromoethylbenzene.<br><br>$C_6H_5-CH=CH_2 \\xrightarrow{Br_2/CHCl_3} C_6H_5-CH(Br)-CH_2(Br)$<br><br>Reaction with excess $NaNH_2$ causes double dehydrohalogenation followed by deprotonation of the terminal alkyne, forming sodium phenylacetylide.<br><br>$C_6H_5-CH(Br)-CH_2(Br) \\xrightarrow{NaNH_2 \\text{ (excess)}} C_6H_5-C \\equiv C^- Na^+$<br><br>Nucleophilic substitution with $CH_3I$ yields 1-phenylpropyne.<br><br>$C_6H_5-C \\equiv C^- Na^+ \\xrightarrow{CH_3I} C_6H_5-C \\equiv C-CH_3$<br><br>Reduction with $Na/NH_3(l)$ reduces the internal alkyne to a trans-alkene without affecting the benzene ring.<br><br>$C_6H_5-C \\equiv C-CH_3 \\xrightarrow{Na/NH_3(l)} C_6H_5-CH=CH-CH_3$<br><br>The major product (Y) is trans-1-phenylpropene, which has the molecular formula $C_9H_{10}$.<br><br>Molar mass of $C_9H_{10} = (9 \\times 12) + (10 \\times 1) = 108 + 10 = 118 \\text{ g mol}^{-1}$.<br><br>Answer: $118$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (04 April Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30619,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{HI}$ is a strong reducing agent.","$\\mathrm{H-I}$ bond is too strong to be broken homolytically.","$\\mathrm{I}$ atom combines with $\\mathrm{H}$ atom to give back $\\mathrm{HI}$.","Iodine atom is not reactive enough to add across a double bond."],"answer":3,"solution":"$\\mathrm{HI}$ does not exhibit peroxide effect. $\\mathrm{HI}$ bond although dissociates easily into iodine radicals, they being bigger in size are not much reactive but recombine together to form iodine molecule.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (09 Apr Online)","image":null}]